<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Party upbeat on prospects for
Euro-seats
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHANGES TO the constit-uency boundaries for next June's European elections
have increased the Liberal Democrats' chances of capitalising on their
successes in south-west England, party strategists said yesterday.
But the party appears divided about what approach to adopt in the campaign.
In spite of the insistence this week that the Liberal Democrats' task is to
turn the protest vote it attracts into positive support, campaign planners
said the party would be inviting voters to deliver a verdict on the
government's performance since the general election.
The Conservatives fear the Liberal Democrats could seize a quarter of the 32
Euro-constituencies the Tories won in 1989, if the most recent local
election results are replicated next summer.
Seeking to temper over-optimism about their prospects, however, the Liberal
Democrats point out that they have tended to do worse in Euro-elections than
in local elections. In 1989, they were still reeling after the collapse of
the Alliance and won only 6.5 per cent of the vote, while the Greens won 15
per cent.
In an effort to maximise support and limit the damage caused to its chances
by its pro-European stance, the party's manifesto will not deal exclusively
with European policy but seek to show how the UK taking a lead in Europe
would help on issues such as jobs and law and order. It would also stress
environmental policies.
As the government this morning published details of the plans for allocating
the five extra European Parliament seats in England, Mr Chris Rennard, the
Liberal Democrats' campaigns director, said that the new boundaries improved
his party's prospects in Cornwall, West Plymouth and Somerset.
On the basis of the party's share of the vote in last year's general
election, it could take both Euro-constituencies with swings of less than
3.5 per cent - far below the spectacular increases in support it has
achieved in recent parliamentary by-elections.
Mr Tim Clement-Jones, the director of the European election campaign, said
that the party would not be able to avoid using the word 'federalism',
though the image of a Brussels superstate many people associated with it was
not Liberal Democrat policy.
</TEXT>
