<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Court levy plan aims to boost
crime fund
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONFERENCE called for a levy on court fines to raise money for crime
prevention schemes.
Delegates backed a move to require local councils to set up crime and safety
task forces, charged with developing crime reduction programmes in
partnership with community organisations.
Crime Concern Campaign chairman Mr Tim Clement-Jones, from Streatham, south
London, said a 5 per cent levy on fines for criminal offences, including
motoring offences, would double the Pounds 7.5m currently spent on crime
prevention. A 10 per cent levy would triple that amount.
But there was concern that the levy would lead to higher fines, hitting the
less well off who were sometimes taken to court for minor offences.
</TEXT>
