<DATE>930923
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Beith warns 'panic cuts'
threaten recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Alan Beith, Liberal Democrat Treasury spokesman, warned yesterday that
economic recovery could be endangered by 'panic cuts' to reduce the Pounds
50bn public sector borrowing requirement.
He said there was a strong case for 'limited and targeted additional
borrowing' to boost capital investment.
Delegates overwhelmingly approved a motion calling for the abandonment of
the extension of value added tax to domestic fuel. The motion also called
for a Budget in which any tax increases were 'fair and progressive'.
Like Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, Mr Beith argued that judgment on the
necessity of tax rises should be left until nearer the November Budget.
He suggested that spending should be increased on construction, housing,
public transport and the promotion of energy efficiency. The first signs of
recovery could be 'snuffed out' if the government mishandled the massive
debt problem it had created, he added. Economic recovery - the only means of
getting the deficit down to manageable proportions - would be threatened by
cuts in capital spending and family incomes.
The warm applause Mr Beith received from some delegates reflected their
annoyance at reports that Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, was under
pressure to allocate the role of Treasury spokesman to a more glamorous
figure.
Mr Beith indicated his acceptance of the new emphasis on the need for
policies to secure a return to full employment by agreeing to accept an
amendment on the role of a central bank. This stipulated that its autonomy
in the use of monetary policy to fight inflation must be consistent with a
'wider, democratically set strategy for sustainable growth and economic
justice'.
The party's commitment to a single European currency - reaffirmed by Mr
Beith - was challenged by rank-and-file speakers. Mr Hilary Whittaker from
Beckenham, south east London, said it would be premature to establish a
timetable for a single currency. Mr Beith acknowledged the difficulties
following the disruption of the European exchange rate mechanism, but argued
that it would offer the opportunity for low interest rates and more
investment and jobs.
The route to a single currency envisaged when the Maastricht treaty was
negotiated could no longer be seen as the only way forward.
Mr Beith said people had to be convinced of the positive merits of a single
currency. Monetary union would work in the long run only if people saw it as
beneficial. He envisaged the eventual return of sterling to the ERM and
urged that when it did so there should be 'a quite short transition period'
to a single currency.
Mr Beith said 'recent events have made the ERM a very draughty waiting room
in which it might not be wise to spend too long once the greater security of
a well-insulated single currency is available'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
