<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Patten may back fees from students
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PATTEN, education secretary, yesterday gave the strongest signal yet
that the government is seriously considering raising extra funds from
students for universities.
Mr Patten, who was addressing the Committee of Vice-chancellors and
Principals at Leicester University, said that no options were ruled out. He
added that the taxpayer benefited from higher education in a less direct way
than graduates. However, he suggested that different universities should not
be allowed to charge different levels of fees.
The committee last month commissioned a report by consultants London
Economics on four methods of extra funding from students, and today will
announce which is favoured.
The options include: increased income tax for graduates; loans to pay for
flat-rate tuition; loans for living costs; and loans for additional 'top-up
fees' that may be charged by universities.
Under the last option, universities could charge differential fees to
students, without subsidy from the government. This option was attacked on
Tuesday by Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary.
Mr Patten has also signalled reservations. In a series of questions for the
vice-chancellors, he asked: 'Should selection for entry to higher education
continue, as far as possible, to be made on educational grounds with no
student excluded because of the need to contribute financially? As you know,
the government has been concerned in the past on this point in connection
with the possible introduction of top-up fees by individual universities.'
He also asked the vice-chancellors if they wanted to continue expanding
higher education, and whether there was any evidence that students who
contributed towards their tuition were more motivated.
Mr Patten defended quality checks in university departments by higher
education funding councils. He also backed the higher education charter,
launched earlier this week and attacked by vice-chancellors as an
'opportunity missed', and as a 'sham' by the Association of University
Teachers.
Middlesex University has become the first British college to set up a
recruiting office in Malaysia. The move follows intensive efforts by the
government to attract more students from the Far East.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    MYZ  Malaysia, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
