<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Commercial sector helps raise building orders 9%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PATCHINESS of the upturn in the construction industry was highlighted
yesterday.
Official figures made it clear that total orders were rising, but showed big
differences in the performance of different sectors.
According to provisional figures from the Department of the Environment,
total orders rose 9 per cent to nearly Pounds 4bn in the three months from
May to July, compared with the same period last year.
But orders were still 5 per cent lower than for the previous three months of
this year. The statistics are based on constant 1985 prices, seasonally
adjusted.
The best-performing sector in the latest three months was private commercial
building. Orders in the sector were 27 per cent higher than in the previous
three months and were 20 per cent higher than in the corresponding period a
year ago.
The private industrial sector remains depressed, with orders down 18 per
cent on the previous three months and 1 per cent lower than in the same
period last year.
In housing, new orders in the private sector fell 10 per cent compared with
the previous three months of this year - but were 3 per cent higher than in
the same period last year.
This confirms reports from housebuilders of a lull in activity in early
summer.
Public housing and housing association orders in the latest three months
were 3 per cent lower than in February-to-April, but 65 per cent higher than
the same period of last year.
The worst-performing sector was in infrastructure, where orders were 28 per
cent lower than in February-to-April and 13 per cent lower than in
May-to-July last year.
Mr Christopher Vickers, construction spokesman for the Royal Institution of
Chartered Surveyors, said declines in new orders in the private industrial
and infrastructure sectors were 'extremely worrying'.
Investment in both sectors was 'the essential ingredient for a sustained
recovery', he said.
'We would expect to see signs of an upturn as the economy picks up and
confidence returns to business and industry,' he added.
