<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Ex-Swans workers win Pounds 1.5m payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNIONS representing more than 700 workers made redundant at Swan Hunter, the
Tyneside shipbuilder, since it went into receivership in May have won
compensation for their members totalling about Pounds 1.5m, Chris Tighe
writes.
An industrial tribunal judgment, announced yesterday, ruled that Price
Waterhouse, the receivers, breached section 188 of the 1992 Trades Union
Labour Relations (Consolidation) Act by failing to consult on the
redundancies.
The six shipyard unions involved said the ruling established the principle
that workers' rights could not be waived in receivership.
The payments will be up to a maximum of about Pounds 2,600 per person. The
unions will now seek another 90-day protected period for the 80 Swans
workers who are to be made redundant next week.
Price Waterhouse said last night that criticisms made in the judgment failed
to appreciate the commercial realities of the situation.
