FT  23 SEP 93 / CBI urges help for small businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT initiatives to help small businesses raise the finance they need
to expand should be introduced, the Confederation of British Industry's east
midlands regional council said yesterday.
Welcoming moves by Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England, to
raise employers' concerns over the lending policies of leading banks, the
council said a change was needed in banking practices to help companies
exploit the signs of recovery.
Mr Geoff Nicholls, chairman of the regional council, said: 'A significant
number of our members are saying past banking policies, particularly the
reliance on security-based lending, penalised expansion.'
Initiatives were needed such as establishing a network that could put small
and medium-sized companies in touch with potential investors.
Among the concerns raised by CBI members were the high cost of debt finance
and the preference by banks to link the amount companies could borrow to the
value of their equity rather than their ability to use operating profits to
repay loans.
Mr Nicholls said: 'There's widespread satisfaction that the government and
the Bank are now taking this matter up.'
