<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Milk prices will be set by auction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ANDREW DARE, chief executive of Milk Marque, yesterday said that an
annual auction of milk supplies will be used to set prices when the Pounds
3.3bn market is liberalised next April. The first auction will take place
next month.
Mr Dare's proposals for a 'rolling' auction are the first indication of how
dairy pricing will work in the free market.
He has been widely criticised in the dairy industry for promising higher
prices to farmers following the abolition of the Milk Marketing Board, the
government's compulsory purchasing scheme.
Milk Marque, a voluntary co-operative and the board's successor, says
auctions will allow the free market to determine prices. But because the UK
produces only 85 per cent of its needs, pressure on supplies is likely to
push up prices.
Mr Dare estimates that consumers could pay up to 8 per cent more if dairy
companies pass these price rises on.
Milk prices are currently set by a committee of board and dairy industry
representatives.
Mr Dare said the auction was 'an open and fair system and yet one in which
customers have to compete with each other for the milk supplies they want,
thereby helping farmers to receive full market value'.
Dairy companies wanting to buy supplies from Milk Marque will be asked to
indicate quantities wanted and prices offered. Once the bids are received, a
market price will be allocated.
Prices may be squeezed upwards if there is strong demand, or customers may
scale back demand. Milk left over from the allocations will be sold at lower
prices or on the spot market.
</TEXT>
