<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / World Trade News: South Africa issues telephone licences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE South African government last night approved the award of two cellular
telephone licences to consortia of local and overseas investors, writes
Patti Waldmeir in Johannesburg.
The ANC has protested that the government should not issue licences without
its approval, raising suspicions that the group was trying to delay the
issue to give US and Scandinavian companies a chance to participate once the
ANC has authorised the lifting of sanctions imposed by those countries. Such
a move is likely as early as tomorrow.
Licences went to Vodacom, a consortium in which Vodafone of the UK has a 35
per cent stake along with the public utility Telkom with 50 per cent and
Rembrandt with 15 per cent, and Mobile Telephone Networks, which includes
Cable &amp; Wireless, the local cable company M-Net and a group of black
investors. It is believed that 30 per cent of MTN will be reserved for black
ownership.
Each licence is expected to involve an investment of about R1bn (Pounds
200m), with an estimated R700m coming from abroad.
