<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Clinton unveils healthcare for all
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton last night promised the US 'healthcare that can never
be taken away, healthcare that is always there' as he launched his campaign
for far-reaching reforms in the US medical system.
'This healthcare system of ours is badly broken and it is time to fix it,'
Mr Clinton said in an address to both houses of Congress. He said the
current health system was 'too uncertain and too expensive, too bureaucratic
and too wasteful. It has too much fraud and too much greed.'
Mr Clinton said his plan was based on six principles: security of coverage,
simplicity for patients and doctors, savings on costs, choice of doctor,
quality of care, and responsibility.
The core of Mr Clinton's plan is a national health card guaranteeing every
US citizen a defined package of health insurance benefits, similar to that
provided today by many big companies but with additional coverage of
preventive medicine.
Most people would be enrolled in 'health alliances' which would bring market
forces to bear to bring down costs.
All employers would be required to pay 80 per cent of the premiums for their
workers.
The plan envisages spending Dollars 160bn (Pounds 105bn) over seven years on
subsidies to smaller employers, as well as Dollars 80bn to expand coverage
of long term care and Dollars 72bn to pay for prescription drugs under the
Medicare programme for the elderly.
Mr Clinton hopes to save Dollars 285bn on existing government health
programmes and to raise Dollars 105bn from 'sin taxes', such as increased
tobacco tax.
</TEXT>
