<HEADLINE>
FT  23 SEP 93 / Downey quits as head of investors' watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Gordon Downey, chairman of the Personal Investment Authority, resigned
abruptly yesterday from the proposed self-regulatory body following
regulators' criticism that he was unable to restrain industry interests on
the board.
He has been replaced by Mr Joe Palmer, a board member of the Securities and
Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, and a former chairman of the
Association of British Insurers.
Industry officials said Sir Gordon's departure followed growing concern at
the SIB that the PIA board had been too willing to concede to powerful
interests in drafting its operating guidelines.
As a result, regulators feared that the authority's board had been plagued
by in-fighting, delaying the completion of its proposed rulebook.
Mr Andrew Large, SIB chief executive, has said that creation of the
authority is central to his plans for enhancing investor protection. He has
also said the SIB will not approve the authority unless it draws up tougher
rules.
In a letter to Mr Large yesterday, Sir Gordon said he was resigning because
good progress had been made at the PIA and 'I do not see myself continuing
into the operational phase.' He also said he expected the authority's board
to be re-constructed.
Sir Gordon, a former senior Treasury civil servant, had been chairman of
Fimbra, the self-regulatory body for independent financial advisers. From
the time he was appointed last year, he had been seen as too close to that
sector of the industry.
Also, board members said he had not faced down officials from the life
insurance industry who wished to influence the authority's rulebook. Mr
Palmer, 62, was group chief executive at life insurer Legal and General.
Mr Large said Mr Palmer had supported his efforts to improve protection for
retail investors, and had endorsed a letter to Sir Gordon last December in
which tough requirements for the PIA were spelled out.
</TEXT>
