<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Tesco traded heavily
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOLUME in food retailer Tesco jumped to a hefty 13m shares, making it the
day's most actively traded stock, as analysts downgraded full-year profits
estimates after the company reported interim fig-ures just short of market
expectations.
Profits came in at Pounds 261.5m, against Pounds 252.8m previously, and the
dividend was increased by 9 per cent. However, market forecasts for profits
ranged from Pounds 265m to Pounds 270m. Having initially fallen 7 to 208p,
the shares steadied to end 4 off at 211p. Reseachers were particularly
disappointed by the decline in margins. There was also concern that the
company's refocused pricing proposition may lead to stiffer competition from
rivals; and there were suggestions that Tesco may have overvalued its
property portfolio.
Researchers reduced full year profits expectations, with UBS said to have
cut its estimate by Pounds 30m to Pounds 600m. Mr David Shriver at NatWest
Securities issued a more severe profits downgrade, reducing his year-end
estimate by Pounds 42m to Pounds 612m. He said: 'Tesco is now in a position
to articulate the way forward; the strategy is clearer but in the short term
the impact of investment in margins will not be beneficial to the bottom
line.'
</TEXT>
