<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Russian news leaves Dow
sharply lower
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
REPORTS yesterday afternoon of political turmoil in Russia sparked heavy
selling of US equities, and left blue chip and cyclical stocks sharply lower
at the end of trading, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 38.56 weaker at 3,537.24, but well
above its low for the day of 3,507.07. Secondary indices fared better than
the Dow. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 lost 2.10 at 452.95, while the American
SE composite shed 3.96 to 447.09 and the Nasdaq composite 6.65 to 733.56.
Trading volume on the New York SE was 300m shares.
Monday's big declines in stock and bond prices set the tone for a downbeat
opening to trading yesterday. Fresh losses in bonds, and concern about the
outlook for the economy and corporate earnings, further depressed the
market, which failed to respond to some rare good news from the housing
market - a bigger than expected 7.8 per cent rise in August housing starts
and a strong increase in building permits.
Prices fell even further during the afternoon as reports emerged from Russia
that President Yeltsin had unexpectedly dissolved parliament and called for
new elections. Amid rumours of a possible move by the military to oust Mr
Yeltsin, the Dow plummeted more than 70 points. Circuit breakers and late
buying, however, helped prices to rally strongly from their lows.
The big domestic story of the day was the emergence of the market's first
billion-dollar bid battle since the 1980s. Paramount Communications, which
only a week ago agreed to be bought by Viacom International, has attracted a
rival bid from QVC, the home-shopping network.
Late on Monday QVC made an offer for Paramount valued at Dollars 9.5bn,
compared to Viacom's original Dollars 8.2bn bid. Amid speculation that a
third contender might enter the fray - possibly Turner Broadcasting -
Paramount's stock jumped Dollars 7 3/8 to Dollars 77 in volume of 6.1m
shares.
The news left QVC, quoted on the Nasdaq market, Dollars 1/8 firmer at
Dollars 56 7/8 and Viacom, listed on the American Stock Exchange, down
Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 56 3/4. Turner Broadcasting receded Dollars 1/4 to
Dollars 25 3/8.
Among depressed cyclical stocks, Caterpillar fell Dollars 2 to Dollars 77,
International Paper gave up Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 60 1/4, Aluminum
Company of America slipped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 66 7/8 and General
Electric declined Dollars 7/8 to Dollars 96 3/8.
Pharmaceuticals staged a recovery from Monday's losses. Merck gained Dollars
7/8 at Dollars 31 3/8, Pfizer Dollars 1 7/8 at Dollars 60 7/8, Johnson &amp;
Johnson Dollars 1 at Dollars 38 7/8 and Bristol-Myers Squibb Dollars 1 3/8
at Dollars 58 3/4.
Tambrands dropped Dollars 3 7/8 to Dollars 42 in heavy trading after the
board announced that it had decided not to sell the company, and that
instead it was embarking upon a restructuring of senior management.
Canada
TORONTO fell for the third consecutive day in heavy trading. The TSE 300
index ended 15.5 off at 3,937.3 and declines led rises by 515 to 237 after
volume of 73.9m shares.
Of the 14 sub-group indices, only the golds sector bucked the downward
trend, advancing 3.85 per cent as the New York spot bullion price surged
USDollars 9.20 an ounce.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
    CAZ  Canada.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
