<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
London coffee and cocoa futures were weaker in the afternoon as both bowed
to pressure from New York, but traders remained confident that the overall
trend remained upward. The December delivery COCOA price temporarily dipped
below Pounds 900 a tonne, but held above support at Pounds 890/895 and ended
the day Pounds 13 down at Pounds 904 a tonne. Traders said the corrective
move was to be expected, with investment funds and speculators looking for
an opportunity to take profits. November delivery robusta COFFEE sank to
Dollars 1,255 a tonne at one point as it followed the New York trend. But
follow-through selling failed to materialise and most of the fall was
recovered. At the London Metal Exchange ALUMINIUM prices remained weak in
the afternoon, having slumped on liquidation at midday, and some analysts
were projecting a fall to the Dollars 1,100-Dollars 1,105-a-tonne area for
three months metal. Final business was at Dollars 1,119 a tonne, down
Dollars 10.50 from Monday. The NICKEL market initially extended recent
declines, crashing to a 6 3/4 -year low of Dollars 4,200 for three months
delivery before support developed around Dollars 4,210 a tonne.
Compiled from Reuters
