<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Southern Newspapers ahead at Pounds 7.5m
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
BOOSTED BY a disposal surplus and lower interest charges, Southern
Newspapers, the regional newspaper group, lifted pre-tax profits to Pounds
7.51m for the 53 weeks ended July 3 1993, against Pounds 7m for the previous
year.
In line with the continuing difficult trading conditions on the south coast,
advertisement revenue fell by over 2 per cent, but this was offset by gains
in contract printing revenue and newspaper sales revenue to give an overall
lift in turnover from Pounds 69.55m to Pounds 71m.
Earnings per share were higher at 22.73p (17.75p) and the total dividend is
stepped up to 11.8p (11.25p) with a final payment of 8.8p (8.25p).
Operating profits were lower at Pounds 6.8m (Pounds 7.23m) but a Pounds
693,000 (Pounds 168,000) surplus on the disposal of investments and lower
interest charges of Pounds 143,000 (Pounds 580,000), left the pre-tax figure
ahead of the previous year.
Mr John Salkeld, chairman, stated that since the year end there had been an
improvement in trading levels of both the newspaper and contract printing
divisions which, with firm cost control, 'augurs well for the future.'
