<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / UK Company News: ICD rejects request for seats on board
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Communication &amp; Data, the marketing services company, has
rejected requests from PSB Group for two seats on the ICD board. PSB, the
direct marketing company, owns 1.93 per cent of the ordinary shares of ICD,
yet has voting rights over 22.61 per cent.
ICD has also denied that another deal it has been pursuing has fallen
through.
The ICD board representation was requested by Mr Jonathan Self, PSB deputy
chairman, who and asked for one seat for himself and one for Mr John Porter,
who is thought to own 5 per cent of ICD's equity. Mr Porter is son of Dame
Shirley Porter, erstwhile leader of Westminster's Conservative group.
Mr Self said: 'In discussions, Mr (David) Cicurel (ICD chairman) confirmed
that the major advertising agency who he had hoped would undertake a reverse
takeover of ICD had now withdrawn from discussions.'
For his part, Mr Cicurel, the company doctor who has restored ICD to
profitability, strongly denied that he confirmed to Mr Self the nature of
the transaction, and that he had told Mr Self that the deal was off.
Indeed, Mr Cicurel stressed that talks with the possible merger partner were
continuing.
Mr Self said that PSB intended 'to place ourselves in a position where we
can request an EGM' to gain representation on the ICD board.
</TEXT>
