<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Wall Street expects bidding war on Paramount
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Paramount Communications soared yesterday as Wall Street
anticipated a bidding war for the entertainment group. This followed a
Dollars 9.5bn (Pounds 6.2bn) hostile offer launched on Monday night by QVC
Network, the home shopping television company headed by Mr Barry Diller, a
leading film industry executive.
Paramount's shares closed at Dollars 77, up Dollars 7 3/8.
QVC's bid topped an agreed bid for Paramount launched on September 12 by
Viacom, a cable television service and programming company best known for
its MTV pop music channel.
Wall Street analysts expected Viacom to improve its offer substantially to
remain in the battle and they thought other US media groups might enter the
fray.
Viacom said acidly that the 'marriage of strategic assets of Paramount and
Viacom cannot be matched by the combination of Paramount and a shopping
service'.
However, QVC's bid was helped yesterday - the first opportunity for the
market to express a view on its offer - by the fact that after a morning dip
its shares ended the day slightly higher. The stock closed up Dollars 1/8 at
Dollars 56 1/8 on the Nasdaq over-the-counter market. That meant that its
bid, consisting of Dollars 30 in cash and 0.893 of a share for each
Paramount share, was worth Dollars 80, the same price as when it was
launched.
Viacom's offer of Dollars 9.10 in cash and a mixture of its stock was worth
only Dollars 60.55, with Viacom's A shares falling Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars
56 3/4 and its B shares down Dollars 2 5/8 at Dollars 50 7/8. That gave the
offer an overall value of Dollars 7.2bn (Pounds 4.7bn) compared with Dollars
8.2bn at launch.
However, Mr Diller has a strong reputation in the entertainment industry.
Other leading shareholders are Comcast, a large cable service company, and
Liberty Media, a cable programme concern spun off from Tele-Communications,
the largest US cable service company.
Profile of Barry Diller, Page 33;
Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
