<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Historic cruise helps to soften up canal rebels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANCHESTER Ship Canal's minority shareholders yesterday agreed to sell their
stock to Peel Holdings for: Pounds 23 a share, a Pounds 7 loan note, a
cruise down the canal next year - and a commemorative medal showing Queen
Victoria making a similar trip in 1894.
The deal values the ship canal company at nearly Pounds 240m.
Peel, a Rochdale property company chaired by Mr John Whittaker, already owns
82 per cent of the stock. Mr Whittaker's private interests won control in
1987, after a bitter two-year fight, in a bid then valuing the company at
Pounds 37m.
A handful of resistant shareholders, who inherited their ship canal shares
as family heirlooms, were overwhelmingly defeated at a general meeting at
Manchester's Free Trade Hall. They will be allowed to keep their share
certificates for sentimental reasons.
Under the deal, all shares will have to be sold to Peel, which will absorb
the canal company, ending its quotation on the Stock Exchange 99 years after
the waterway opened. The same price will be paid for both ordinary and
preference shares.
The original offer valued the ordinaries at Pounds 7 and the prefs at Pounds
3. The bulk of the latter are already owned by Peel. Since they have equal
voting rights with the ordinaries, they provided a cheap way to gain
control. The rest are held mainly by Mr Nicholas Berry, the largest ordinary
minority shareholder, who was defending chairman of the company in the last
months of the battle.
Since the company has statutory powers, the High Court has to approve the
deal. The court required a simple majority of shareholders and 75 per cent
majority by value of holdings - criteria which were easily achieved
yesterday.
The Pounds 7 loan stock, to be redeemed for Pounds 10.50 in five years'
time, represents the potential value of 300 acres of land which Peel hopes
to develop as a retail centre, in spite of legal obstacles it has yet to
surmount.
Mr Berry said shareholders' patience had been rewarded. He criticised
financial institutions which had sold earlier to Peel for short-termism and
being run by 'grey men'.
Observer, Page 25
</TEXT>
