<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Tesco to fight rivals on price: 'Aspirations of customers in
the 1990s are very different from the affluent 1980s'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TESCO, the UK's second-biggest superstore chain, yesterday broke ranks with
its main competitors by saying it was repositioning itself on price, and
admitting the growing threat posed by discount food retailers.
Sir Ian MacLaurin, chairman, claimed Tesco had opened a price gap of 4 to 5
per cent on basic products between it and competitors such as J Sainsbury
and Argyll, owner of Safeway. His comments prompted speculation about a
price war.
He admitted Tesco had been slow to react to the recession, but hoped to
outpace its competitors in a grocery sector where 'the ball-game has
changed'.
'Quite clearly the aspirations of customers in the 1990s are very different
from the affluent 1980s,' Sir Ian said.
He added that the spread of discounters such as Aldi, of Germany, and Netto,
of Denmark, selling a limited range of goods at low prices, had put pressure
on superstores to ensure their prices were competitive.
'Whoever you are, you now have the Aldis, Nettos and Eds sitting on your car
park. We have got to be as cheap as anybody on the basics, but offer
additional lines and services.'
His comments came as Tesco disclosed a smaller-than-expected increase of 3.4
per cent in interim profits to Pounds 261.5m on turnover up 9.5 per cent to
Pounds 4bn. It said its gross margin was down 0.2 percentage points as a
result of its price initiatives - the first decline for about eight years.
Sir Ian did not go as far as Mr Archie Norman, chief executive of Asda, who
has warned the 'halcyon days' of food retailing are over, with a saturated
food market unable to support the planned number of store openings. He did,
however, warn there would be an inevitable 'sort-out'.
Analysts said Tesco's new approach, which follows similar moves by
superstore operators such as Asda, Gateway, and Wm Morrison, would put
pressure on Sainsbury and Safeway.
'If you go down this path you must be prepared to go all the way,' said Mr
Bill Currie, analyst at BZW. 'And I don't really see how Sainsbury and
Safeway can sit back and not respond.'
Sir Ian said the change in thinking at Tesco resulted from a review of
customer attitudes. The survey led to a new store design, including new
services and departments. It also led to the decision to sharpen prices and
introduce the cut-price Tesco Value brand to compete directly with the
discounters. Mr David Reid, finance director, denied that discounters had
eroded Tesco's sales, but admitted they were 'changing the price
benchmarks'.
Results, Page 28; Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
