<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Tarmac in the black and makes cash call
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TARMAC, Britain's biggest housebuilder, yesterday launched a Pounds 215m
rights issue to fund the next phase of its recovery. It also announced a
return to pre-tax profits in the first half.
One third of the rights issue proceeds have been earmarked to fund a land
buying programme to take advantage of the upturn in the UK housing market.
The rest of the Pounds 215m will cover deferred capital expenditure on plant
and machinery for Tarmac America, and help the group to expand its
international construction business. It will also strengthen Tarmac's
capital structure, including the redemption of Dollars 150m (Pounds 97.4m)
redeemable preference shares.
The one-for-four rights issue is priced at 120p-a-share. Yesterday the share
price closed 1 1/2 p lower at 145p.
Tarmac reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 2.5m in the six months to June 30
compared with a loss of Pounds 15.1m in the first half of 1992. Turnover
slipped 4 per cent to Pounds 1.3bn, but sales of continuing businesses rose
2 per cent.
After taxation, minority interests and preference dividends, the group
recorded a loss per share of 0.7p, against a 2.2p loss last time. The
interim dividend is maintained at 3p.
Mr Neville Simms, chief executive, said Tarmac was nearing the end of its
remedial phase and the management was now turning its attention to the next
stage.
'Today's rights issue is the final piece of the jigsaw for our remedial
strategy and the foundation stone of our strategy going forward,' he said.
'The rights issue will enable us to achieve our medium-term objectives for
growth whilst maintaining prudent financial policies,' he said.
In the first half, net interest costs fell to Pounds 24m, from Pounds 31.9m,
reflecting lower rates and a sharp decline in net borrowings. The group's
divestment programme has so far raised Pounds 227m towards a target of
Pounds 300m.
Overall operating profits increased by 69 per cent to Pounds 24.8m (Pounds
14.7m). The housing recovery and improved prices in quarry products,
together with the benefits resulting from Tarmac's rationalisation and
refocused strategy, all contributed to the improved performance. Exceptional
items added another Pounds 1.7m to profits, against Pounds 2.1m last time.
Within the group's three core businesses, turnover in the quarry products
division increased to Pounds 260.3m (Pounds 240.7m), but operating profits
fell to Pounds 7.6m (Pounds 8.7m), reflecting a change in product mix. The
housing division more than doubled its operating profits to Pounds 15.3m
(Pounds 7m), even though turnover declined to Pounds 255.5m (Pounds 281.9m).
But profits fell to Pounds 7.6m (Pounds 9.3m) in the construction division
despite an increase in turnover to Pounds 480.9m (Pounds 448.5m).
The rights issue is fully underwritten by Lazard Brothers and Samuel
Montagu.
People, Page 21; Lex, Page 26
</TEXT>
