<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Ministers see savings in drive against housing benefit fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSING BENEFIT fraud is to be the main focus of government plans to save up
to Pounds 1bn next year by preventing false social security payments.
Ministers hope to be able to announce the detailed measures in time for the
Tory party conference due to take place early next month.
The move is likely to be announced by Mr Peter Lilley, the social security
secretary, who will be keen to find a statement popular with the party,
given the anger among grassroots Tories that no scheme has yet been
announced for compensating those worst affected by the imposition of value
added tax on domestic fuel.
Housing benefit is administered by local authorities, and among the probable
changes is a reform of the complicated arrangements through which councils
are repaid by government for what they spend, to give them a greater
incentive to cut down on fraud.
Better systems under which central government can keep a check on how
authorities are running the benefit are also likely.
Until now, Whitehall officials say, the emphasis has been strongest on
tackling fraud in benefits administered by central government, and the
greatest savings in these areas may already have been made.
A report from the Audit Commission, a government-spending watchdog, said
early this year that it welcomed moves already taken to reduce the
disincentive for councils to mount fraud investigations and improve housing
benefit administration. However it added that more should be done.
A group of officials from the interested departments have been carrying out
a review of housing benefit for some months, as part of the long-term review
of public spending.
Ministers in the Department of the Environment and the Department of Social
Security have concluded, however, that they can do little to cut housing
benefit rates without undermining the government's social housing policy.
Instead, in the public spending discussions with the Treasury, they are
offering to make the savings necessary from an anti-fraud initiative.
One official said that discussions were still going on, but housing benefit
would probably alter to put the onus on local authorities to track down
fraudsters.
</TEXT>
