<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Jeremy Mills, producer of the BBC1 documentary series 'The Skipper' screened
last night, is also the producer of today's Inside Story which looks at
Terry Waite's five years as a hostage in Beirut. During Waite's time in
captivity there was growing speculation about his relationship with Oliver
North, the man at the centre of the American 'arms for hostages' deals, and
talk of a rift between Waite and the Archbishop of Canterbury.
Waite describes the experience of being held hostage and talks about
subsequent resulting difficulties (9.30 BBC1).
A new season of BBC2's 'ScreenPlay' begins with Love Lies Bleeding, set in
Belfast. A republican prisoner, Conn, held in the Maze, is let out on parole
for 24 hours and attempts to establish who killed his girlfriend many years
ago (9.00).
Tempting music on Radio 3. The BBC Orchestras at 7.30 begins with a live
performance by the BBC Philharmonic of Sibelius's tone poem 'The Swan Of
Tuonela'. Then at 9.45 in the Bath International Festival a positive feast
of real music by Bach, Handel and Telemann.
