<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Labour ducks education funding row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN ELEVENTH-hour decision by Labour to delay publication of a discussion
document on higher education overshadowed its launch yesterday of a paper on
A-levels.
The consultative document suggested that graduates might be asked to meet
part of the cost of university education, although it was made clear that
this was not official party policy.
The decision not to publish the document will raise fresh doubts about the
Labour leadership's willingness to confront difficult issues, before the
party's annual conference in Brighton next week.
Officials said the decision - taken late on Monday by senior party figures
including Mr John Smith, Labour leader - was intended to avoid distracting
attention from other aspects of its education green paper. They said the
document would be published after the party's conference.
Copies of the document had already been distributed to university
vice-chancellors, who are meeting in Leicester.
It says that higher education is 'not a pure collective good', and that the
system is constrained by supply rather than demand. It says: 'Inequity has
to be removed, and the system has to be paid for at some time by someone.'
The move was understood to have dismayed some frontbench speakers. One
Labour MP said he now doubted whether the party would formally publish the
document.
It is now thought likely that Mr Jeff Rooker, the education spokesman who
wrote the paper, will submit a lightly redrafted version to Labour's
Commission on Social Justice in a personal capacity.
University vice-chancellors will announce which extra source of funds they
favour tomorrow. Mr John Patten, education secretary, will address them on
the topic today.
Mr Patten yesterday said: 'I do think there's a very strong moral argument
for saying that those who benefit from higher education through a lifetime
should make a contribution.'
</TEXT>
