<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Battersea power station threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONTRACTORS at Battersea power station in London are threatening to remove
steel supports holding up part of the structure because of a dispute with
its owners.
Sir Robert McAlpine and Sons, which is owed about Pounds 20m for civil
engineering work undertaken on the site, is in dispute with the Hwang family
of Hong Kong which in effect now owns the site as mortgagee.
The family, represented in Britain by Mr Victor Hwang, took possession of
the building at the weekend and locked the gates on McAlpine workers who had
been looking after site offices and machinery.
McAlpine has rejected a Hwang offer of 1p in the pound for its debt.
It is demanding its machinery back and says it wants to remove structural
supports installed under its contract with Mr John Broome's Battersea
Leisure, the former owner of the site.
Mr Simon Broakes, McAlpine's group property and special projects manager,
said: 'We have literally been supporting that building for many years. We
would not do anything to compromise the structural integrity of the
building. But Victor Hwang has to decide whether he wants to buy the
steelwork or replace it with his own.'
McAlpine has agreed that it will only remove the steelwork under the
supervision of English Heritage which has responsibility for listing
historical monuments.
English Heritage said yesterday that any structural alteration to the
building would require listed building consent.
