<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Night flying curbs prompt court move
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE living near the three main airports around London face increased
levels of night noise from aircraft if the government is allowed to
introduce a controversial system of flying restrictions, the High Court was
told yesterday.
Under the new system favouring 'quieter' aircraft, the number of take-offs
and landings at Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted would rise sharply.
Richmond and Tandridge councils in Surrey, and Windsor and Maidenhead and
Slough councils in Berkshire, and the London borough of Hillingdon were
applying for a judicial review of a decision by Mr John MacGregor, transport
secretary, to introduce new restrictions from October 24. The councils have
financial support from eight other local authorities.
Mr Richard Gordon, representing the councils, told Mr Justice Laws that the
present regime dated from 1988 and imposed a straightforward curb on the
number of night flights.
He said there were fears that the number of after-dark flights at Heathrow
could rise under the new system from 5,750 a year to 24,000. Since 1981 the
government had a policy of encouraging more flights made by quieter
aircraft, and that same policy was meant to underly the new restrictions.
Mr Gordon said it was uncontentious that night noise levels had decreased
since 1988. But Mr MacGregor was now planning to use powers provided under
the 1982 Civil Aviation Act to curb noise nuisance in effect to increase the
number of flights from airports which would disrupt people's sleep, said Mr
Gordon.
Under the act, the transport secretary has the power to lessen or extinguish
noise, and that he had therefore acted outside his powers in making
proposals which would increase existing noise levels.
The hearing was adjourned until today. Manchester airport was yesterday
voted the best airport in the UK, with Gatwick second and Heathrow third in
the 1993 Travel Awards sponsored by Travel Trade Gazette, the industry
paper, and Express Newspapers.
</TEXT>
