<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Farmers predict smaller harvest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL Farmers' Union yesterday predicted a fall of nearly 12 per cent
in this year's grain harvest to 19.5m tonnes.
The union blamed bad weather conditions during planting and the effects of
Common Agricultural Policy reforms, notably the requirement that arable
farmers must leave part of their land fallow to qualify for compensation for
cuts in European Community support prices.
Mr David Naish, union president, said: 'Apart from climatic factors, British
farmers are having to adjust their businesses to take account of the
three-year CAP reform package agreed by EC agriculture ministers last year
and this is obviously having a significant effect on the way their land is
farmed.'
The Ministry of Agriculture announced yesterday that the total area planted
with cereals had fallen by 13 per cent to 3m hectares this year, the first
year of CAP set-aside. The wheat area was down 15 per cent and barley down
10 per cent.
Last week Dalgety Agriculture estimated a much bigger grain harvest of 20.9m
tonnes. Predictions vary each year, and Dalgety calculates its yields per
hectare in a different way to the union, giving a higher figure for wheat.
The union's arable crops survey estimated a 1m-tonne drop in the wheat
harvest to 13.1m tonnes in spite of a 9 per cent increase in yields. It
expected the barley crop to fall from 7.4m tonnes to 5.9m tonnes.
The agriculture ministry's figure for the total harvest last year, which was
a poor one for cereals, was 22.1m tonnes. The 1991 harvest was 22.6m tonnes.
</TEXT>
