<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / French are wooed in tourism drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH Tourist Authority today begins a campaign to persuade even more
French visitors to cross the Channel, with the official opening in central
Paris of a new UK tourist centre, Maison de la Grande Bretagne.
The centre will be opened by Mr Peter Brooke, heritage secretary. More
excitement is likely to be generated by Jane Birkin, the Paris-based British
actress, who has promised to make an appearance. Food will be provided by
Marks and Spencer, which has a store down the road.
The centre's ground floor offers video displays and a bookshop. British Rail
International has an office there, as do some ferry companies.
Mr Bruce Taylor, the authority's manager in France, says the centre was set
up because 86 per cent of French visitors to the UK make their travel
arrangements independently rather than through travel agents. The new centre
will enable them to make all their bookings at the same time.
Last year 2.5m French residents made a trip to the UK, second only to the
2.7m American visitors.
But the average French tourist to the UK spent only Pounds 28.10 a day last
year, compared with an American tourist's average expenditure of Pounds
55.20 a day.
One of the reasons is that many French visitors are students. In 1991, 24
per cent of French tourists were under 16 and more than 40 per cent were
under 25. On present form 60 per cent will come back as higher-spending
adults.
Mr Frederic Simonet, a technology student, and Ms Anne Morvan, studying
English, were at the centre last week to book a weekend in London in
October. London has three attractions, they say. It is nearby, they can
practise their English and the shops are different.
</TEXT>
