<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Wage costs stable
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WAGES PER UNIT of output across the economy barely changed between the final
quarter of last year and the second quarter of this year, underlining the
weakness of inflationary pressures.
In the second quarter, unit wage costs were down 0.9 per cent compared with
the same period a year ago. This was the same year-on-year drop as in the
first quarter, according to seasonally adjusted Department of Employment
figures.
Particularly strong downward pressure on unit wage costs has come from the
manufacturing sector, which saw a 1.2 per cent fall in these costs in the
second quarter compared with three months earlier.
In the second quarter, unit wage costs in manufacturing were 2.1 per cent
down on a year earlier, compared with a 2.8 per cent year-on-year drop in
the first three months of 1993.
Output per employed person throughout the economy in the second quarter was
up 4.5 per cent on a year earlier, the same as the yearly rise for the
January to March period. Output per head in the second quarter was up 0.4
per cent on the first quarter, continuing the trend towards higher
productivity seen over the past year.
In the second quarter, manufacturing productivity was up 7.2 per cent on the
corresponding period last year. In the first quarter the equivalent figure
was 7.9 per cent.
</TEXT>
