<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Foreign groups intensify battle in PC market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPETITION IN Britain's personal computer market, already the fiercest in
Europe, has intensified sharply with the arrival of two large companies from
the US and continental Europe.
Plans to take a share of the UK's Pounds 3bn personal computer market were
announced yesterday by Gateway 2000, a large US manufacturer.
Vobis Microcomputer of Germany announced plans to enter the UK market last
month. Gateway will market its full range of computers direct to users while
Vobis is selling its 'Highscreen' brand through Dixons, the electrical
retailer.
Direct-selling manufacturers use neither retailers nor distributors but
advertise their products in newspapers and trade magazines, completing the
deal by telephone or mail order. The technique was pioneered by Dell
Computer Corporation of the US which has grown in a decade to revenues last
year of Dollars 2bn. More than 30 per cent of PCs are now sold in the UK
this way.
Gateway says it sells more IBM-compatible PCs this way in the US than any
other manufacturer. It has set up an assembly and distribution centre in
Dublin from which it intends to attack the UK market before moving into
France and Germany. It was established in 1985 and employs 2,500 people in
the US. It made pretax profits of Dollars 105m last year on a turnover of
Dollars 1.1bn.
Vobis, one of the largest PC manufacturers in Germany, is following its
compatriot Escom AG, which this year started a chain of small retail stores
in the UK. About 15 have already opened and Escom is aiming to have 26 by
the end of next month.
The PC market in the UK has grown vigorously over the past 12 months -
driven by substantial advertising campaigns and falling prices. According to
Context, a London-based consultancy, sales this year are likely to be 22 per
cent up on last year.
Some 93,000 units were shipped in July alone, 37 per cent more than the year
before. The value of the computers shipped increased by only 17 per cent,
however, an indication of the sharp decline in unit prices. Context says the
average price of a system is now Pounds 1,400; most experts believe prices
will not fall much lower but customers will get more features for the same
price. Most machines are based around the leading Intel 486/SX
microprocessor.
According to the marketing consultancy Romtec, Compaq of the US has the
lion's share of the UK market with 13 per cent. IBM is only 1 percentage
point behind. Apple has 7 per cent and Dell has 6 per cent. Toshiba, Elonex
and Olivetti hold 4 per cent apiece while none of the other 200 or so
manufacturers have more than 3 per cent of the market.
Mr Ted Waitt, the chief executive of Gateway, said the UK launch had been
planned for three years. He said Gateway hoped to sell by innovative
advertising, low prices and first-rate customer service. A top-of-the-range
system would sell for less than Pounds 2,500.
Mr Michael Spiro, finance director for the UK company Elonex, which will
compete with Gateway in the direct market, said the US company's declared
prices did not seem all that exciting: 'What can they do? They have to use
the same components from the same sources as everybody else.'
</TEXT>
