<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Motor design breakthrough hailed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH scientists and component manufacturers yesterday welcomed a
breakthrough in the design of electrical motors which, they claim, could
revolutionise power systems in domestic appliances and cars by making them
smaller and lighter.
Launching a three-year programme to develop the new motors, scientists from
the universities of Warwick and Cardiff said the innovation could lead to a
60 per cent reduction in the size of motors needed to power products ranging
from food mixers and power tools to car-steering systems.
The development programme is backed by a consortium of 22 companies
including Black and Decker, Lucas Industries, Kenwood and Vent-Axia, and
will be part-funded by the Department of Trade and Industry.
Unlike traditional motors which rely on electrical connectors to drive them,
the new motors have no electrical contact between the power source and the
drum - the part of the motor that revolves.
The motors are driven by coils of wire energised by pulses of electricity
400 times a second. The process, called switched reluctance drive, creates
an energy field which rotates the drum and generates the power to move
components.
The principle of switched reluctance drive is not new, and other research
companies and manufacturers are testing it. However, this is thought to be
the first time such a system has achieved standards acceptable to industry.
The system has been pioneered by Dr Charles Pollock, a lecturer in power
electronics at the University of Warwick, and Professor Hugh Bolton of the
University of Wales College of Cardiff.
Dr Pollock said: 'By breaking away from conventional technology we can
radically change the design of products.
For the automotive industry, this could be the equivalent of fly-by-wire -
it could lead to electrical steering and doing away with traditional
mechanical systems.'
Mr David Shaw, a senior electronics engineer at Black and Decker, said: 'The
potential is enormous. There's no blow-out or stalling with these motors; we
may even be able to fit them into the handle of a power drill.'
Vent-Axia said that such motors could be fitted in its 400,000-product
range. 'It will give us cost savings and increased efficiency,' said Mr
David Vincent, technical director.
</TEXT>
