<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Downturn forces Nissan to halve output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN, the Japanese carmaker, is to halve production at its Pounds 900m car
plant at Sunderland in the final two months of the year under the impact of
the sharp decline in sales of new cars in continental Europe.
Nissan, which exports about 80 per cent of its output from its Sunderland
plant, is the latest victim of the downturn in European demand for new cars
which has forced widespread job losses, production cuts and restructuring
across the European motor industry.
Elsewhere in the UK, Vauxhall has imposed extensive short-time working at
its two assembly plants this month, while Ford, Rover and Peugeot have cut
several thousand jobs, and output at Vauxhall, Ford and Peugeot has fallen.
Nissan said yesterday that it would move to single-shift working for two
months from November 8 by eliminating the night shift in order to cut output
from 1,200 cars a day to about 600 cars.
Some 2,400 of its 4,600 employees will work only every other week in
November and December. They will remain on full basic pay, which averages
Pounds 13,164 a year for an assembly-line worker, but will lose night-shift
bonuses which average Pounds 183 a month.
Nissan halted all recruitment at the Sunderland plant in May, and the
workforce is now shrinking through non-replacement at the rate of 180 jobs a
year.
The production cut is the first big setback suffered by Nissan at
Sunderland, the first Japanese car plant in Europe, where it started small
volume output in 1986. For the full year of 1993 it is now cutting output by
8.9 per cent to 246,000 from the total of 270,000 forecast earlier this
year, and it warned yesterday that production could fall further next year.
Output of the Primera large family car will drop to only 93,500 this year
from 141,800 in 1992, a 34 per cent decline. Production of the Micra small
car, which started in August last year, will total 152,500 compared with the
37,200 produced in the last five months of 1992.
Nissan had planned originally to produce at close to full capacity for the
first time this year at Sunderland. Production for the year will still be 37
per cent higher than the 179,000 cars it produced last year, but as the
plant reaches maturity it is no longer able to insulate itself from the
downturn in European demand.
The company said yesterday that the impact of recession in Europe was likely
to wipe out the pre-tax profit of Pounds 29.6m earned last year by Nissan
Motor Manufacturing (UK), the Sunderland production plant, which was now
expected only to break even this year.
Nissan is grappling with severe problems worldwide. The consolidated Nissan
group is in overall loss for the second year running. It is being forced to
close a plant in Japan and in Spain, where its Nissan Motor Iberica
operations ran up losses of Pta23.1bn (Pounds 117m) in the first half of the
year, it has announced that it is to lay off 5,100 workers at its Barcelona
and Madrid plants for 11 days during October and November in order to cut
output by 4,000 vehicles.
The recovery in UK demand for new cars this year - sales rose by 11.8 per
cent in the first eight months of the year - has only protected carmakers to
a small extent against the recession in the rest of west Europe. Nissan's
high level of exports from its Sunderland plant means it has been hit hard
by the overall 16 per cent drop in sales of new cars in west Europe in the
first eight months of the year.
