<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: Ashdown setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PARTY leader Mr Paddy Ashdown (above) was flatly rebuffed yesterday in his
ambitions to open up government to non-elected experts, Philip Stephens
writes.
The setback came as his close aides said the party intended to counter the
charge that it had become a 'one-man band' by raising the public profile of
its parliamentary representatives.
Mr Charles Kennedy, the Liberal Democrat president; Mr Matthew Taylor, its
campaigns co-ordinator, and Mr Menzies Campbell, the defence spokesman, were
singled out as the principal beneficiaries of such a move as senior figures
acknowledged that most of the party's MPs are unknown outside their
constituencies.
Amid an undercurrent of concern that some of the party's representatives
needed to sharpen their presentation of key policies there were also
suggestions that Mr Ashdown may reshuffle the responsibilities of his
Westminster team. That put a question mark on Mr Alan Beith's long-term hold
on the economics portfolio.
Mr Ashdown's hopes of promoting a more pluralistic political establishment
by proposing that unelected individuals be allowed access to ministerial
office was rejected. He had backed a plan to reserve up to a third of
ministerial posts for appointees from outside Westminster.
But delegates shared the objection of a number of his colleagues that such a
move would undermine accountability. The leader was also accused privately
of relying on 'gimmicks' to raise the party's profile.
</TEXT>
