<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Liberal Democrats at Torquay: The centre may not hold -
Conference Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CENTRE of gravity in British politics is shifting. For most of the
Thatcherite 1980s Labour and Liberal Democrats spent their time chasing the
Conservatives to the right. The name of the opposition game now is to occupy
and remodel the centre ground.
The most striking feature of this week's Liberal Democrat conference has
been the self-conscious shift leftwards. A party which fought the last
general election on a set of market-driven economic assumptions scarcely
distinguishable from those of Mrs Thatcher has suddenly re-discovered a role
for government in determining the country's prosperity.
Full employment - for long derided as the pipedream of unreconstructed
socialists - is suddenly an at least half-respectable political objective.
Liberal Democrats can again hold out the occasional olive branch to the
trades unions. A couple of years ago the party leadership was as
enthusiastic as the Conservatives about the privatisation of British Rail.
Now the talk is of refusing to be driven by outdated ideology.
You could say, of course, that Mr John Major started it all when he kidded
the right of the Tory party that he was really one of them. Three years on
Mr Kenneth Clarke is in command at the Treasury, Mr Michael Heseltine at
trade and industry and Mr David Hunt at employment. There could be no more
potent insult to the Thatcherite dispossessed.
Manufacturing industry counts again, restrictions on public-sector pay have
brought with them the whiff of 1970s-style incomes policies, the level of
public borrowing has snuffed out talk of anything but the most transparently
token cut in income tax this side of the next general election.
Conservatives have once again been heard uttering such words as 'community'.
There is more than that. The Conservative right is in ideological disarray.
The rows over Europe and the exchange rate mechanism have sown as much
confusion among the disgruntled on the Tory backbenches as in Mr Major's
government.
It is little wonder that the real thinkers on the right - Mr Michael
Portillo the most prominent among them - are in a state of quiet despair.
The shift should not be exaggerated. Much of the Thatcher revolution has
been absorbed by the nation's political fabric. Weak unions, the replacement
of state direction with a presumption in favour of competition and
enterprise with state control, and disavowal of crude demand management have
become part of the consensus.
So much so, there is concern among both the Labour and Liberal Democrat
leaderships that the Tories' troubles will tempt their parties back into
their bad old ways. Mr Tony Blair, the most eloquent advocate of
modernisation in the Labour shadow cabinet, is battling fiercely against a
resurgence of the one-more-heave-tendency within his party at Westminster.
Mr Paddy Ashdown also faces a growing mood among his party's activists to
abandon the fiscal responsibility of the 1980s in favour of spending pledges
for pensioners, schoolteachers and health-service workers.
There is another dimension. The political scene is still suffering the
aftershocks of a deep and unusually indiscriminate recession.
It will take years of resumed growth before it is possible to judge whether
the unprecedented disenchantment of the electorate with politics and its
practitioners runs deeper than the disillusion invariably triggered by
recession.
Mr Ashdown is convinced it does. His premise this week has been that the
mood of anti-politics reflects not only the failure by the nation's leaders
to deliver the substance of politics - economic prosperity, decent public
services and a fair distribution of wealth and income. Voters will not be
reconciled with their representatives until the processes and structures of
politics have been radically overhauled.
Hence the Liberals' constant pre-occupation with constitutional change. It
is an understandable - perhaps unavoidable - strategy for a third party
which depends for power on change and has anyway to differentiate its
product from that of two entrenched competitors.
Changes in the political process though are no substitute for the more
mundane but far more immediate issues on which the voters judge politicians.
The right in British politics has lost its way. The opposition parties will
never have a better chance to recapture the initiative. Whether they can
seize the opportunity is another question.
</TEXT>
<XX>
