<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Senior PLO leader shot dead in Gaza
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GAZA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GUNMEN killed a leader of the Palestine Liberation Organisation mainstream
Fatah faction in the Gaza Strip yesterday, AP reports from Gaza. The
shooting came during a rally celebrating the recent agreement between Israel
and the PLO, hospital officials said.
It was the first assassination since the PLO and Israel signed an agreement
September 13, handing over Gaza and Jericho to Palestinian self-rule within
four months.
Mohammed Abu Shaban, 35, was shot dead as he left the rally, Arab reports
said. Two cars filled with masked men forced his car off the road and killed
down in a hail of bullets when he stepped out to see what was happening.
Leaders of Palestinian groups opposing the agreement have vowed to sabotage
it by violence, and have threatened the life of Mr Yassir Arafat, the PLO
leader.
But Arab reports said Abu Shaban might have been the victim of rivals within
his own Fatah group, rather than Moslem fundamentalists opposing the accord.
Abu Shaban, who led the political committee in Gaza advising the Palestinian
negotiators to the 23-month-old Middle East peace talks, was a popular
figure known for his charity work in the area. Since the PLO-Israeli
agreement was announced two weeks ago, he led the organisation of
pro-agreement rallies.
