FT  22 SEP 93 / Olympic revenue to increase to Dollars 2.5bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTE CARLO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOTAL REVENUES to the Olympic movement, from the sale of television rights
and sponsorships, were Dollars 1.9bn (Pounds 1.23bn) in 1989-92 and
projections for the next four years, which cover the Lillehammer and Atlanta
Games, show an increase to nearly Dollars 2.5bn, the International Olympic
Committee said yesterday in disclosing details of its financial standing for
the first time, writes Keith Wheatley in Monte Carlo.
The Lausanne-based IOC has assets of Dollars 125m and received an average
annual income for its own use of Dollars 39m over the latest period. In its
first-ever annual report Mr Francois Carrard, chief executive, says that
less than 7 per cent of gross income is retained by the IOC to fund
administration. The remainder is distributed to Games organising committees,
national Olympic committees and individual sports federations.
Yesterday the IOC, meeting in Monaco where it will choose the site of the
2000 Games, agreed to establish an independent Olympic Foundation.
Lausanne's Olympic Museum, opened in June, and other assets worth up to
Dollars 74m will be transferred to the foundation by the end of this year.
