<DATE>930922
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Crisis in Russia: Survey suggests country is split
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD ROSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Yeltsin's attempt to break the deadlock in Russia by suspending
parliament threatens to split public opinion down the middle, to judge by
the results of a recent nationwide survey.
A public policy survey of Russians conducted in mid-summer showed that 52
per cent favoured presidential rule by decree - but 48 per cent were
opposed. Furthermore, 48 per cent of Russians said they believed parliament
should have the right to veto presidential decisions.
The survey, based on interviews with 1,975 respondents in urban and rural
areas from late June to late July, was conducted by the Russian Centre for
Public Opinion Research. It showed Russians effectively split into four
groups, none of them in the majority: 32 per cent supported rule by
presidential decree without a veto by parliament; 28 per cent advocated
legislative rule by parliament without presidential decrees; 20 per cent in
effect favoured gridlock - a combination of presidential decrees and a
parliamentary veto - and 20 per cent opposed both presidential decrees and
parliamentary rule.
Mr Yeltsin's call for an early parliamentary election is endorsed by 65 per
cent of Russians. In addition, 44 per cent believe there should be an early
presidential election. Here again, opinion splits four ways, for one-third
of Russians would like elections soon for both president and parliament, and
28 per cent are against any election.
A total of 84 per cent of Russians said they thought the Constitutional
Court should resolve disputes between the president and parliament.
Two-fifths would prefer Mr Yeltsin to be replaced by an old-style communist
regime.
Professor Richard Rose of Stathclyde University is directing a 15-nation
study on east European public opinion.
</TEXT>
