<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Crisis in Russia: Economy at heart of conflict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS no accident that Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian prime minister
who approved earlier this month a package of emergency measures to cut
budget expenditure, stipulated the bulk of remaining funds should go to the
army.
But although Mr Yeltsin now bids for the army's support, his conflict with
parliament had in recent weeks crystallised over the more mundane issue of
the country's budget deficit.
Last night he cited parliament's 'so-called economic policy' - led by its
demands for increased budget expenditure without a corresponding increase in
revenues - as a glaring example of 'political games played at the expense of
the people'.
His suspension of parliament cancels at least one appointment he had been
anxious to avoid; parliament was due on Friday to consider the government's
request to borrow just Rbs4,700bn from the Russian central bank to finance
the deficit.
Deputies were intending to force the government to borrow Rbs15,000bn, to
make parliament appear the kinder side in the conflict.
The government has sought to keep such loans down to avoid the financial
system's collapse. The money would simply have been printed by the central
bank, thereby fuelling inflation. Mr Sergei Alexashenko, the deputy finance
minister responsible for the budget, said in an interview last week: 'I am
afraid that if it does this, parliament will say the government has this
money and must therefore spend it.'
The government's strategy has been to keep down the deficit and raise
revenues with a package of emergency measures, including stiff tax increases
and sales of up to 100 tonnes of government gold stocks to Russian
commercial banks.
The government's main challenge now, should parliament stay dissolved, is to
pursue unpopular policies.
If, in addition to the various measures being undertaken by the Finance
Ministry, central bank loans were kept to Rbs5,000bn, the deficit could fall
to 8 per cent of GDP by the end of the year.
This would put it within the 10 per cent limit agreed by the government with
the International Monetary Fund as a condition for at least Dollars 1.5bn in
additional financial assistance by the end of the year.
Sales of these dollars within Russia would help keep inflation down by
absorbing surplus roubles held in the economy, and relieve pressure on the
government to apply the tough tax increases it probably does want to impose
in the months leading up to parliamentary elections.
Another big challenge facing the central government - especially if some
regions rebel against Mr Yeltsin's announcement - is to get all the regions
and republics to pay their taxes.
Speaking before Mr Yeltsin's announcement, Mr Alexashenko said the
government had options to bring rebel republics and regions into line over
taxation by, for instance, withholding deliveries of cash, or confiscating
valuable exports bound for the west.
But again, Mr Yeltsin will be relying on republican and regional leaders to
stay on his side.
Although it has been held up as a key justification for Mr Yeltsin's
dramatic action, economic policy is likely once again to take a back seat
until the political dust settles.
</TEXT>
