<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Crisis in Russia: Yeltsin will stand or fall on reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Boris Yeltsin's decision to tackle his parliamentary opponents head-on
was widely seen yesterday as the moment when he finally staked his political
survival on the success of his economic reforms, Edward Balls reports.
An observer close to the reform effort, who would not be named, said
international financial institutions were not surprised Mr Yeltsin had acted
because it had become clear the two sides' failure to compromise on
constitutional differences could not be sustained.
If these could be settled, Russia could press on with economic reform.
</TEXT>
