<HEADLINE>
FT  22 SEP 93 / Yeltsin plunges Russia into crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW.
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA was plunged into an acute political crisis last night as its
president and vice-president both claimed supreme state authority and the
allegiance of the people and the armed forces.
President Boris Yeltsin precipitated the long-awaited confrontation with
parliament and General Alexander Rutskoi, his vice-president and main
opponent, when he dissolved parliament, called elections for December and
took emergency executive powers.
But his unilateral action was immediately challenged by parliament, the
constitutional court and Gen Rutskoi, who proclaimed Mr Yeltsin's act
unconstitutional and declared himself president.
Early this morning the army appeared to be staying neutral and there was no
evidence of imminent armed conflict. But it was unclear who was in control
and the scene seemed set for a prolonged power struggle.
In a nationwide television address Mr Yeltsin told the Russian people he had
dissolved the existing legislature - the Supreme Soviet and the Congress of
People's Deputies - and had called for elections to a new bicameral
parliament, or Federal Assembly, for December 11 and 12, to be followed by
early presidential elections.
The country's constitutional court ruled that Mr Yeltsin had violated the
constitution and could be impeached. Its chairman, Mr Valery Zorkin, told
parliament after an emergency session the court had concluded that Mr
Yeltsin's decree and statement did not correspond with the constitution and
were a 'basis for impeaching the president'. Mr Ruslan Khasbulatov, the
parliamentary speaker, appealed to all military, interior and security
troops and militia to disobey the 'criminal orders' of the president and
parliament voted to order the central bank to stop financing government and
presidential structures.
Shortly afterwards parliament reported that Mr Sergei Glazyev, the country's
trade minister had resigned in protest at Mr Yeltsin's action.
Mr Khasbulatov called on all regional and republican parliaments throughout
Russia to hold immediate sessions to denounce the president's decree and
told workers to mount strikes in defence of the constitution'. However, the
prime minister, Mr Viktor Chernomyrdin, in an effort to calm an inflamed
situation, indicated he remained loyal to Mr Yeltsin. 'I will carry out what
is necessary for the government and the orders of the president,' he said
after a government meeting. When asked if he meant Mr Yeltsin, Mr
Chernomyrdin replied 'yes'.
Mr Vladimir Shumeiko, the first deputy prime minister - who returned to his
duties yesterday after being cleared of corruption charges - said that the
heads of the 'power' ministries of Defence, Security and the Interior, who
command all of the country's armed forces, had expressed support for Mr
Yeltsin.
There were signs, however, that Mr Yeltsin had not gained the full consent
of all of his supporters before last night's dramatic announcement. A senior
parliamentarian, speaking on condition of anonymity, said many members of
the presidential team had advised against the move.
He said senior members of the collegium of the Ministry of Defence had come
to parliament after a meeting yesterday - and had retailed an account of a
conversation between Mr Yeltsin and General Pavel Grachev, the defence
minister, in which, in response to obvious pressure from the president for
his support, Gen Grachev had asked: 'What do you want me to do - bring in
the army, or what?'
Last night a statement from Russia's armed forces said they would obey the
constitution and 'as in the past maintain strict neutrality'. Communists
manned the barricades outside parliament in protest at Mr Yeltsin's decree,
but there was little sign of stepped-up military activity.
The parliament responded swiftly to Mr Yeltsin's announcement by voting late
last night to strip him of his powers. A hastily-convened emergency session
swore in Gen Rutskoi, still suspended by Mr Yeltsin from his
vice-presidential duties on corruption allegations, as president.
Gen Rutskoi quickly announced his first decree: 'To declare null and void
all decrees issued by President Boris Yeltsin on September 21. Leaders of
regions and (semi-autonomous) republics within the Russian federation are
obliged to act within the constitution.'
Earlier Gen Rutskoi said Mr Yeltsin had dismissed himself from power by
breaching the constitution, and that he, Gen Rutskoi, was now president.
'This is a direct violation of the constitution,' he said from within the
White House, or Russian parliament. 'It is an open state coup.'
Mr Yeltsin said in his address he had taken all necessary measures to ensure
security - and lorryloads of troops were deployed outside buildings such as
the Interior Ministry.
Anarchy, Mr Yeltsin said, could not be allowed in a country possessing
nuclear weapons. His action was necessary to preserve both democracy and the
still weak Russian market.
