FT  22 SEP 93 / Countdown to Yeltsin's decision
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
June 1991: Yeltsin elected president of the Russian republic
Aug. 21: Yeltsin helps thwart coup against Gorbachev.
Oct. 18: Gorbachev and presidents of eight Soviet republics create economic
union.
Dec. 1991: The Soviet Union ceases to exist; Gorbachev leaves office.
Feb. 1992: Demonstrations in Moscow and other cities as living standards
fall.
March 1993: Yeltsin declares 'special rule' pending April 25 referendum,
results of which show Russians in favour of Yeltsin's reforms.
Aug. 27: Parliament overturns Yeltsin's veto of its inflationary budget.
Sept. 3: Parliament rejects Yeltsin decree suspending Rutskoi as vice
president.
Sept. 10: Yeltsin acts against constitution in refusing to sign budget law.
