<HEADLINE>
FT  21 SEP 93 / US calls Mideast aid meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday called a conference of potential donors to drum up aid in
support of the peace agreement between Israel and the Palestine Liberation
Organisation.
Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, said he and Mr Lloyd
Bentsen, the Treasury secretary, would convene a donors' conference to help
co-ordinate aid for Palestinian self-rule in the Gaza Strip and Jericho.
'Today, on behalf of President Clinton, I announce our intention to lead a
wide-ranging effort not simply to give peace a chance but to ensure that it
will not fail,' Mr Christopher said in a speech at New York's Columbia
University.
Administration officials said the purpose of the conference was not just
economic, but to demonstrate backing for last week's agreement and to
maintain momentum for the peace process.
Mr Christopher said the US would itself contribute Dollars 250m in cash,
loans and guarantees over the next two years.
Senior administration officials said the conference was likely to be held in
Washington in the next two weeks, taking advantage of the arrival in the US
of finance and foreign ministers attending the annual meetings of the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank, as well as the United
Nations General Assembly.
They hoped the conference would produce several hundred million dollars of
commitments to cover the next 18 months, making a successful start towards
the World Bank's Dollars 300m a year estimate of investment needs over the
next 10 years.
Mr Christopher's speech yesterday, the first in a series of foreign policy
statements planned ahead of President Clinton's address to the UN on Monday,
declared the US's strong commitment to an active and assertive role in
international affairs.
'We must remain engaged not out of altruism, nor out of what one scholar has
called the 'imperial temptation', but because there are real American
interests that will suffer if we are seduced by the isolationist myth,' Mr
Christopher said.
The International Monetary Fund has approved a three-year, Dollars 569m loan
to help Egypt open up and reform its economy, Reuter reports from
Washington.
Although Egypt does not plan to draw down the loan, Cairo needed IMF
approval of its economic reform programme to win over Dollars 3bn in debt
forgiveness from the US and other creditor nations. Under a 1991 deal,
creditor nations agreed to write off 50 per cent of Egypt's Dollars 25bn
debt.
Assad cool on deal with Israel; Arafat in Jordan, Page 4
